acteristic forenames:  French Armand, Carolle, Edouard, Jean-Pierre, Marcel, Veronique.","French: habitational name from any of a number of places in northern France, so named from Latin <i>monasteriolum</i>, a diminutive of <i>monasterium</i> ‘monastery’. Compare   Montroy  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Montroy","meanings":["Altered form of French   Montreuil  .","French: habitational name from either of the places so called, in Puy-de-Dôme and Charente-Maritime. This surname is very rare in France."]}]},{"name":"Emma","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Old French name, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, originally a short form of compound names such as   Ermintrude   containing the word <i>erm(en)</i>, <i>irm(en)</i> ‘entire’. It was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain, but its popularity in medieval England was greatly enhanced by the fact that it had been borne by the mother of Edward the Confessor, herself a Norman. In modern times, it was only in moderate use early in the 20th century but rose sharply in favour in the 1970s and has since remained perennially popular."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Emma de Montreuil was born in 1090, her father, John de Montreuil, was 40 and her mother, Mrs. John de Montreuil, was 31. She had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Sir Gilbert De La Legh Venables Crompton. She died in 1160, at the age of 70, and was buried in France."},"et":{"1090–1160":"1090–1160","1089–Male":"1089–Surnud","1100–Female":"1100–Surnud","1113–1147":"1113–1147","1050–Male":"1050–Surnud","1060–Female":"1060–Surnud","1090":"1090","1147":"1147","1113":"1113","1100":"1100","1089":"1089","about 1100":"umbes 1100","1160":"1160","1050":"1050","1060":"1060","Kinderton Cum Hulme, Northwich, Cheshire, England":"Northwich, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England","France":"Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1090–1160":"1090–1160","1089–Male":"1089–Kuollut",